# PAIDEIA — Course Context (Codex)

## Purpose

This folder is a per-course exam-prep workspace. Given raw materials (lecture notes, textbook
chapters, HW problems, HW solutions — PDF or markdown), Codex builds a structured knowledge
base and drives drilling, grading, and compression toward the exam date.

## Course metadata

```
COURSE_NAME: $COURSE_NAME
EXAM_DATE:   $EXAM_DATE
EXAM_TYPE:   $EXAM_TYPE
WEAK_ZONES:  $WEAK_ZONES
OCR_ENGINE:  $OCR_ENGINE
```

`OCR_ENGINE` is one of `codex-native` (default — renders PDFs to PNG and reads them via
Codex CLI's bundled vision, no extra API billing for ChatGPT Plus/Pro/Business subscribers),
`qwen3-vl` (local Ollama, fully offline), or `tesseract` (lightest, lowest fidelity). The
value in `.course-meta` is authoritative; any skill can override per-call with
`--ocr=<engine>`.

## Directory map

```
materials/  converted/  course-index/  quizzes/  mock/  twins/  chain/  derivations/
cheatsheet/ weakmap/    answers/       errors/
```

Only `materials/` and `answers/` are yours to edit by hand. Everything else is regenerated by
skills; treat it as derived. See the plugin README for full semantics.

## How skills are invoked

Codex exposes each skill as `$paideia-<verb>`. Type the verb in chat and Codex loads the
skill body before acting. Core verbs:

- `$paideia-ingest` — every PDF in `materials/**` → LaTeX markdown in `converted/**`, via
  the bundled `paideia-mcp` server's parallel vision pipeline.
- `$paideia-analyze` — build `course-index/{summary,patterns,coverage}.md` from `converted/`.
- `$paideia-phase` — print the current artifact-derived phase (`setup` → `cool`).
- `$paideia-hwmap`, `$paideia-pattern`, `$paideia-derive` — navigate the knowledge base.
- `$paideia-quiz`, `$paideia-blind`, `$paideia-twin`, `$paideia-chain`, `$paideia-mock` — drills.
- `$paideia-grade` — OCR a scanned answer PDF, strategy-grade, append `errors/log.md`.
- `$paideia-weakmap`, `$paideia-cheatsheet` — priority reports and one-pager.

Heavy pipelines (parallel PDF OCR, multi-engine OCR dispatch, course-index extraction, phase
detection) live in the `paideia-mcp` stdio server, so skill bodies stay short and Codex never
has to hold raw page images in context.

## Workflow philosophy

1. **User does not type math in the CLI.** Codex produces markdown files. User reads.
2. **User produces PDF scans** of hand-written work, dropped into `answers/`.
3. **Codex OCRs via the engine in `OCR_ENGINE`** and **strategy-grades** — pattern match,
   not line-by-line algebra. OCR noise in hand-written math makes strict grading useless.
4. **HW density = exam probability.** Drill `🔥🔥` (3+ HW on a section) first; `⚪` (no HW)
   is reference-only — the professor's omission is itself a signal.

## Drill tiers (used by every drill skill)

| Tier | HW count on § | Treatment |
|------|---------------|-----------|
| 🔥🔥 Exam-primary | 3+ | Drill hardest; ≥70% of mock points |
| 🔥 Exam-likely | 2 | Drill next; ~25% of mock points |
| 🟡 Exam-possible | 1 | Warm-pass review |
| ⚪ Low-risk | 0 | Reference only; professor signaled off-exam |

If the user insists on drilling a ⚪ section, comply once and warn that exam probability is low.

## Conventions Codex follows

- **Citations.** Every explanation cites `converted/<file>.md §K`. This trains the user's
  mental index of where things live in the source materials.
- **Pattern IDs.** Use the `Pk` label from `course-index/patterns.md` alongside any
  descriptive name when referring to a technique.
- **Never reveal reference solutions before the user attempts.** Drill skills enforce this.
- **Korean prose, LaTeX math.** `$...$` inline, `$$...$$` display. Korean for explanation.
- **Error logging is mandatory** on every failed attempt. Append YAML to `errors/log.md`:
  ```yaml
  - problem_id: <id>
    pattern:    <Pk>
    error_type: pattern-missed | wrong-variable | wrong-end-form | algebraic | sign | definition
    summary:    "<1 line>"
    date:       <ISO>
  ```
- **Idempotent operations.** `$paideia-ingest` skips already-converted files. `$paideia-analyze`
  warns before overwriting `course-index/`.
- **Length discipline.** Drill output ≤ 40 lines. Grade reports ≤ 15 lines.
- **No CLI math answers.** If the user starts typing a solution in chat, redirect them to
  the PDF-upload workflow.

## What Codex should NOT do

- Ask the user to type math in chat.
- Produce answers that assume the user will solve problems in chat.
- Skip `$paideia-ingest` or `$paideia-analyze` verification before running drill skills.
- Reveal solutions proactively — always wait for the user's attempt, or an explicit "show me".
- Write verbose prose when the user needs an index entry.

## What Codex SHOULD do

- Check `course-index/` exists before running any drill skill.
- Cite sources (`converted/` files) in all explanations.
- Keep outputs compact; the user is time-pressured.
- Log errors systematically.
- When uncertain about course-specific notation, ask once and remember for the session.
